what is the definition of epidemiology epidemiology is the study of factors affecting the health and illness of populations and serves as the foundation and logic of interventions made in the interest of public health and preventive medicine it is considered a cornerstone methodology of public health research and is highly regarded in evidence based medicine for identifying risk factors for disease and determining optimal treatment approaches to clinical practice the work of communicable and non communicable disease epidemiologists ranges from outbreak investigation to study design data collection and analysis including the development of statistical models to test hypotheses and the 'writing up' of results for submission to peer reviewed journals epidemiologists may draw on a number of other scientific disciplines such as biology in understanding disease processes and social science disciplines including sociology and philosophy in order to better understand proximate and distal risk factors Science Medicine Cancer Homeopathy Autism Sociology Alzheimer's disease Pseudoscience Folic acid National Institutes of Health Duesberg hypothesis Economics Medical analysis of circumcision Philosophy of science Multiple sclerosis Case-control History of science Clinical trial Political science Traditional Chinese medicine Social psychology Acupuncture Alternative medicine Bipolar disorder Behaviorism Model (economics) AIDS reappraisal Prostate cancer Chinese University of Hong Kong Statistics Mobile phone radiation and health Philosophy of mathematics Osteopathy Falsifiability Social sciences Clinical depression AIDS Academic publishing Eugenics Psychiatry Tobacco smoking Stroke Religious studies Mathematics Abortion Psychosis Bayesian inference Schizophrenia Addiction Autism epidemic Obesity Intelligent design Causality Race Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Sociocultural evolution Biology and sexual orientation Drug abuse Nutr